When Tony Stark died and was replaced by an [[Earth-96020|alternate]] [[Anthony Stark (Earth-96020)|younger counterpart]],{{r|Avengers #395}} through a previosuly recorded holo-message Stark appointed [[Abraham Zimmer (Earth-616)|Abe Zimmer]] and [[Bambina Arbogast (Earth-616)|Bambi Arbogast]] as Senior [[Stark Enterprises Board of Directors (Earth-616)|Board]] Members, [[Bethany Cabe (Earth-616)|Bethany Cabe]] and [[Harold Hogan (Earth-616)|Happy Hogan]] as Co-Chief Executive Officers and [[James Rhodes (Earth-616)|Jim Rhodes]] and [[Virginia Potts (Earth-616)|Pepper Potts]] as Trustees.{{r|Iron Man #327}}

Stark Enterprises was later sold to a relatively small [[Japan|japanese]] firm named [[Fujikawa Industries (Earth-616)|Fujikawa Industries]],{{r|Iron Man #217|219}} which obtained 99% of Stock Ownership, while [[Rumiko Fujikawa (Earth-616)|Rumiko Fujikawa]], granddaughter of Fujikawa Industries' President [[Kenjiro Fujikawa (Earth-616)|Kenjiro Fujikawa]],{{r|Iron Man Vol 3 4}} was given 1% of the stock.{{r|Iron Man Vol 3 56}} Fujikawa Industries, renaming itself '''Stark-Fujikawa''', appointed Tony's cousin [[Morgan Stark (Earth-616)|Morgan Stark]] as General Manager of Stark Companies' North American Operations.{{r|Iron Man Vol 3 1}}

At some point, Stark-Fujikawa rebranded Stark Enterprises as '''Stark Industries'''.{{r|Iron Man Vol 3 56}}

When Kenjiro and Rumiko Fujikawa agreed to cede Tony Stark 51% of the Stark Industries' Stock Ownership, Stark ultimately reobtained control of his former company as the majority shareholder.{{r|Iron Man Vol 3 56}}

